==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*haitan'' ‘command, name’, from Indo-European ''*kei-, *ki-'' ‘put in motion, be moving’.  Cognate with Old Frisian ''[[heta|hēta]]'', Old Saxon ''[[hetan|hētan]]'' (Dutch ''[[heten]]''), Old High German ''[[heizzan]]'' (German ''[[heißen]]'' ‘call, be called’), Old Norse ''[[heita]]'' (Swedish ''[[heta]]''), Gothic [[𐌷𐌰𐌹𐍄𐌰𐌽]].  The IE root is also the source of Greek ''[[κίειν]]'' ‘put in motion’, Latin ''[[ciere]]'' ‘rouse, make active’.

